    "---\n",
    "title: \"Detecting Media-Driven Spikes in Wikipedia Traffic\"\n",
    "subtitle: \"Time-series anomaly detection on three months of real Wikipedia pageview data\"\n",
    "date: 2026-06-06\n",
    "categories: [Time Series, Anomaly Detection, Polars, Parquet, Robust Statistics]\n",
    "toc: true\n",
    "toc-depth: 3\n",
    "code-fold: true\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "::: {.section-label}\n",
    "Spike Detection · Real Public Data\n",
    ":::\n",
    "\n",
    "::: {.tldr}\n",
    "**TL;DR** — Built a spike detector on real Wikipedia pageview data: 103 articles, 92 days,\n",
    "July through September 2024. To grade it honestly, I planted four fake spikes with known\n",
    "sizes and dates (an answer key), kept at realistic 2× to 5× lifts, and the detector caught\n",
    "all four, including a ×2 slow burn and a one-day blip that a persistence-only rule would\n",
    "miss. Bonus: the same detector surfaced the real news of that summer for free, the Paris\n",
    "Olympics, the July 13 rally shooting, Taylor Swift's Harris endorsement, and Obama's DNC\n",
    "speech all show up as ranked events.\n",
    ":::\n",
    "\n",
    "::: {.callout-data}\n",
    "**Data source:** Daily per-article pageview counts from the official\n",
    "[Wikimedia Pageviews REST API](https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/) (public domain, CC0).\n",
    "The fetch script (`data/fetch_wikipedia.py`) pulls July 1 to September 30, 2024 for a\n",
    "curated set of 103 well-known en.wikipedia articles and caches it as month-partitioned\n",
    "Parquet. The real data is untouched except for four labeled spike events I plant on top\n",
    "so the validation step has ground truth. Which four, and why, is spelled out below.\n",
    ":::\n",
    "\n",
    "## The Business Problem\n",
    "\n",
    "In media measurement you face the same question constantly: **did a traffic spike actually\n",
    "mean something, or is it noise?** A 30% jump in sessions might be a successful TV spot, a\n",
    "viral social moment, or just a normal Saturday.\n",
    "\n",
    "Answering that manually doesn't scale. With daily data across many pages, products, or\n",
    "regions, you need an automated framework that:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Builds a dynamic baseline per series instead of one global threshold\n",
    "- Flags spikes that are statistically unusual, not just big in absolute terms\n",
    "- Handles both flavors of spike: the one-day blip and the multi-day slow burn\n",
    "- Ranks what it finds, because an alert list nobody can triage is the same as no alert list\n",
    "\n",
    "Wikipedia pageviews are a perfect testbed. The data is real, it's public, and the summer\n",
    "of 2024 (Olympics, an assassination attempt, a presidential race) is packed with genuine\n",
    "media-driven spikes to find.\n",
    "\n",
    "## The Approach\n",
    "\n",
    "::: {.approach-grid}\n",
    "\n",
    "::: {.step}\n",
    "::: {.step-num}\n",
    "1\n",
    ":::\n",
    "::: {.step-body}\n",
    "#### Ingest real data to Parquet\n",
    "Pull daily pageviews from the Wikimedia REST API for 103 articles over 92 days, write to month-partitioned Parquet, query lazily with Polars.\n",
    ":::\n",
    ":::\n",
    "\n",
    "::: {.step}\n",
    "::: {.step-num}\n",
    "2\n",
    ":::\n",
    "::: {.step-body}\n",
    "#### Plant a known answer key\n",
    "Inject four labeled spikes with chosen multipliers and durations (×2 to ×5, 1 to 4 days) so detection quality can be measured, not eyeballed.\n",
    ":::\n",
    ":::\n",
    "\n",
    "::: {.step}\n",
    "::: {.step-num}\n",
    "3\n",
    ":::\n",
    "::: {.step-body}\n",
    "#### Build robust baselines\n",
    "Rolling 21-day median plus MAD-scaled sigma per article. Median and MAD don't get corrupted by the very outliers we're hunting.\n",
    ":::\n",
    ":::\n",
    "\n",
    "::: {.step}\n",
    "::: {.step-num}\n",
    "4\n",
    ":::\n",
    "::: {.step-body}\n",
    "#### Detect in two tiers, then rank\n",
    "A persistent tier (z > 5 for 2+ consecutive days) and an extreme tier (z > 12 for even a single day). Group flagged days into events and rank by peak z for triage.\n",
    ":::\n",
    ":::\n",
    "\n",
    ":::\n",
    "\n",
    "## Step 1: Real data, real ingestion\n",
    "\n",
    "Wikipedia publishes per-article pageview counts through the\n",
    "[Pageviews REST API](https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/). The per-article endpoint is\n",
    "daily grain (the hourly variant was retired; hourly still exists as multi-GB bulk dumps\n",
    "at ~7M rows per hour, which is where this exact pipeline would point in production). Each\n",
    "row is one `(article, day)` pair: `article`, `timestamp`, `views`.\n",
    "\n",
    "The fetch script already cached everything as partitioned Parquet, so loading is a lazy\n",
    "Polars scan. I time it because the query speed is part of the point."
   ]
