    "## Step 3: Plant the answer key\n",
    "\n",
    "Here's the part most anomaly detection writeups skip. If I only run the detector on raw\n",
    "data and point at dramatic charts, you have to take my word that the flags are good.\n",
    "Real spikes don't arrive labeled. So before detection, I plant **four fake spikes with\n",
    "exact known dates, sizes, and durations** on top of the real data. That gives the\n",
    "validation step an answer key: we know precisely what a perfect detector should find,\n",
    "because we put it there.\n",
    "\n",
    "The four are chosen to stress different failure modes, not picked at random:\n",
    "\n",
    "| Article | Planted scenario | Multiplier | Duration | What it tests |\n",
    "|---|---|---|---|---|\n",
    "| Albert_Einstein | \"Breaking News\" | ×4 | 2 days starting Jul 21 | a sharp burst on a steady page |\n",
    "| Taylor_Swift | \"Celebrity Mention\" | ×3 | 3 days starting Aug 5 | a spike on a page that is already busy and noisy |\n",
    "| Bitcoin | \"Viral Social\" | ×2 | 4 days starting Aug 25 | the smallest lift but the longest, a slow burn |\n",
    "| Elon_Musk | \"TV Mention\" | ×5 | 1 day on Sep 9 | a one-day blip, the case a persistence rule misses |\n",
    "\n",
    "The scenario names are just labels I made up for the shape of each event, they aren't\n",
    "real news stories. ×N means every real pageview count inside that window gets multiplied\n",
    "by N, so the spike sits on top of the page's genuine day-to-day texture instead of being\n",
    "a clean synthetic curve.\n",
    "\n",
    "The sizes are deliberately modest. In my experience real media-driven lifts land\n",
    "somewhere between 2× and 5× of normal activity, a true 8× or 10× day is rare. An earlier\n",
    "draft of this study planted ×8 and ×12 spikes and they were almost insulting to the\n",
    "detector, anything would catch those. The ×2 Bitcoin slow burn is the one that actually\n",
    "makes the detector work for it."
   ]
